+## Deferred from: story-3.7 dev (2026-05-14)
+
+- **`SecurityCheckService.RequiredPrivileges` not aligned with PRD §5.4's new `SystemUser | Read` row.** Story 3.7's Dev Notes (recommended option 1) ask both `docs/prd.md` §5.4 AND `SecurityCheckService.RequiredPrivileges` to be updated in the same commit. The PRD row was added; the service-side list was NOT, because adding `"Read SystemUser"` would require updating six existing test assertions in `SecurityCheckServiceTests` (`RequiredPrivileges_HasExactly12Entries` → 13; `ComputePrivilegeSets_AllPresent_EmptyMissingAndExtra` 12 → 13; `ComputePrivilegeSets_OneMissing_DetectedInMissing` 11 → 12; `ComputePrivilegeSets_SharePointBaseline_NotReportedInExtra` 12 → 13; `ComputePrivilegeSets_CaseInsensitive_RequiredMatch` 12 → 13) plus a new `[InlineData("prvReadSystemUser", "Read SystemUser")]` row in `MapPrivilegeName_Read_MapsCorrectly`. The handoff prompt for the autonomous run capped diversions outside the story's "Files modified" list to "a single inline-data row addition" and instructed STOP-and-defer beyond that. In practice the tool is unaffected because `prvReadSystemUser` is auto-granted to every service-account role via Dataverse's Basic User membership (SecurityCheckService.cs line 99-100 documents this rationale for the historic deliberate exclusion). Fix path: bump the literal `12` count assertions to `13`, add the InlineData row, and add `"Read SystemUser"` to the `RequiredPrivileges` array. Single-file impact: `src/DataverseDocAgent.Api/Features/SecurityCheck/SecurityCheckService.cs` + `tests/DataverseDocAgent.Tests/SecurityCheckServiceTests.cs`.
+
 ## Deferred from: code review of story-3.6 (2026-05-14)
 
 - **`PrefixAnalyzer` Microsoft `cr` regex over-matches real ISV prefixes.** `^cr[a-z0-9]*$` swallows any prefix starting with `cr` and containing only `[a-z0-9]` — e.g. `crm_`, `crystal_`, `cradius_`, `crew_`. AC-2 of the story explicitly accepts this over-match (the bucket rule is intentional, not defective) on the basis that real-world Power Apps default-environment auto-prefixes (`cr3a7_`, `crf2b_`) are the dominant `cr*` case and an ISV picking `crm_` is a documented edge case. The current behaviour is contract-locked by `Analyze_BucketsMicrosoftPrefixes` (`crm_widget` and `crystal_thing` are pinned as Microsoft). Revisit if a real customer environment exposes the over-match (e.g. a `crm_*` ISV solution gets visibly mis-bucketed); the tightening path is `^cr[a-f0-9]{3,4}$` (PowerApps default-environment prefix shape).
